  "prompt": "What is Precision-Recall (PR) curve?",
  "response": "The **Precision-Recall (PR) curve** is a graphical representation used to evaluate the performance of a binary classification model, particularly in scenarios where the classes are imbalanced. It plots **precision** on the y-axis and **recall** on the x-axis for different classification thresholds.\n\n### Key Components:\n1. **Precision**:  \n   - Precision measures the proportion of correctly predicted positive instances out of all instances predicted as positive.  \n   \\[\n   \\text{Precision} = \\frac{\\text{True Positives (TP)}}{\\text{True Positives (TP)} + \\text{False Positives (FP)}}\n   \\]\n   - High precision means fewer false positives.\n\n2. **Recall (Sensitivity)**:  \n   - Recall measures the proportion of correctly predicted positive instances out of all actual positive instances.  \n   \\[\n   \\text{Recall} = \\frac{\\text{True Positives (TP)}}{\\text{True Positives (TP)} + \\text{False Negatives (FN)}}\n   \\]\n   - High recall means fewer false negatives.\n\n### PR Curve:\n- The PR curve is created by varying the classification threshold (e.g., the probability threshold for assigning a class) and calculating precision and recall at each threshold.\n- A good model will have both high precision and high recall, resulting in a curve that is closer to the top-right corner of the plot.\n\n### Interpretation:\n-[One type of bulleted list]\n  - **Area Under the Curve (AUC-PR)**: The area under the PR curve summarizes the model's performance. A higher AUC-PR indicates better performance.\n  - **Imbalanced Data**: The PR curve is particularly useful for imbalanced datasets, where the ROC curve might be misleading because it does not account for the class imbalance.\n  - **Trade-off**: There is often a trade-off between precision and recall. Increasing one might decrease the other, depending on the threshold.\n\n### Example Use Case:\nIn a fraud detection system where fraudulent transactions are rare (imbalanced dataset), the PR curve helps evaluate how well the model identifies fraud (high recall) while minimizing false alarms (high precision).\n\n### Comparison with ROC Curve:\n- The **ROC curve** plots true positive rate (recall) against false positive rate, while the PR curve focuses on precision and recall.\n- The PR curve is more informative than the ROC curve for imbalanced datasets.\n\nIn summary, the PR curve is a powerful tool for assessing model performance, especially in scenarios where class imbalance is significant.",
